But it seems unlikely, because for slapstick to work – as it does in, say, Laurel & Hardy and Some Mothers Do ’Ave ’Em – you have to be able to believe what you’re seeing. The characters must have a reason for what they’re doing; they’re sane people who set out with good intentions, but, thanks to a combination of clumsiness, stupidity and bad luck, everything goes disastrously wrong. What happens may be absurd, but it follows a certain logic, one calamity leading to the next. Whereas in Father Figure there’s little if any logic. The characters just do irrational, silly, horrible and violent things. That’s it.
